0.body: raen is a build tool for NEAR smart contracts. With RAEN, you can: build: compile a contract, generate its Application Contract Interface (ACI), and inject it into a custom section of the contract's WebAssembly (Wasm) binary. fetch [coming soon] : use the ACI of a deployed contract to generate source code bindings for cross contract calls and client interfaces. To get started, first install RAEN . If you have experience with NEAR and want to get to the RAEN-specific stuff you can skip to the status message contract .
0.title: Introduction

1.body: At its core the NEAR blockchain is a big database. A contract is a program with its own storage space. You have access to read and write to this storage like you would any key/value data structure. The simplest example of this is a counter. A contract that can read, increment, and decrement a value.

25.body: All change calls need to be signed by an account, this proves that no other account made the transaction. From the contract's perspective, when executing it has access to the current context with includes the signer account id. Since this account id is unique to the signer it can be used as a key in storage. Let's take a look.

3.body: A struct in Rust defines a data structure with fields. You might have seen a class or an object in JS. Unlike other languages, the data structure has no methods attached to it, rather it just defines the shape.
3.title: struct

4.body: The field val is of type i8, which, while sounding a bit like a iPhone version, is a signed 8-bit integer meaning it can be between -128 and 127. This means once val is incremented to 127, the next time it will wrap around to be -128. [1]
4.title: val

5.body: Lastly, pub is short for public, meaning that the item is visible outside of the file [2] . If you want to read a little more about number types, check out The Rust Book's description . Technically pub is a namespace , but that's not important right now.
5.title: pub

6.body: Rust does allow you to attach methods to the data. This is done with an implementation (impl).
